03544cam a2200433 i 1587455634OCoLC20260504163443.0m     o  d        cr mn|||||||||260430t20252025ctuac   ob    001 0 eng d  a0300293054q(electronic bk.;qA&AePortal)  a9780300293050q(electronic bk.;qA&AePortal)  z0300278349q(paperback)  z9780300278347q(paperback)  aYUSbengerdaepncYUSdYUSdOCLCO 4aN6923.P5bB534 2025eb1 aBick, Tenley C.,eauthor.1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PCjKJMj3gYdHqfYqKxm7rbd10aMichelangelo Pistoletto :bfiguration and cultural politics /cTenley Bick. 1aNew Haven ;aLondon :bYale University Press,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (xi, 228 pages) :b155 illustrations (some color), portraits  astill imagebsti2rdacontent  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages [195]-218) and index.00tIntroduction : A contradictory corpus --tFormative figures : Artmaking in postwar Turin --tFragments of figuration : Mirror paintings, plexiglass structures --tFigures of protest : Pop and politics in the mirror paintings --tExtremely poor figures : A world minus objects, minus men --tThe real and performed figure : Lived and staged action in and after the zoo --tConclusion : Figure as model.  a"Widely regarded as the central protagonist of Arte Povera, the twentieth-century Italian art movement characterized by its rejection of representation, Michelangelo Pistoletto (b. 1933) is known for his movement-defining Minus Objects and iconic mirror paintings, as well as his recent social practice addressing migration and climate change. What has unified Pistoletto's work over six decades ... is his persistent, and seemingly paradoxical, investigation of figuration, most often as a system of representation of the human body. 'Michelangelo Pistoletto: Figuration and Cultural Politics' traces the figure as a throughline across the artist's painting, photomontage, sculpture, installation, performance, and social practice, from the formative years of his career in the 1950s to today. It situates Pistoletto's exploration of the figure within the culture and leftist politics of Italy and beyond in the 1960s and 1970s to examine why, in an era that was defined, for many, by the end of humanism, Pistoletto held on to the figure as an embattled platform for rethinking art and the world"--Publisher's description.  aDescription based on print version record and online resource (A&AePortal, viewed on April 30, 2026).10aPistoletto, Michelangelo,d1933-xCriticism and interpretation. 0aArt, ItalianxHistory and criticismy20th century. 0aArte poveraxHistory and criticism. 0aArtistszItalyxHistory and criticismy20th century. 0aHuman figure in artxCriticism and interpretationy20th century.1 aPistoletto, Michelangelo,d1933-eartist1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PBJfrHKFYpF9qMGVfJCJqwC2 aYale University Press,epublisher.08iPrint version:aBick, Tenley C.tMichelangelo Pistolettoz9780300278347w(DLC)  2024942631w(OCoLC)1449672880403A&AePortal (Yale University Press)uhttps://aaeportal.com/?id=-10126305551cam a2200577 i 1579014042OCoLC20260504163532.0m     o  d        cr mn|||||||||260312t20252025iluac   obc   001 0 eng d  a0300302460 (electronic bk. ;qA&AePortal)  a9780300302462 (electronic bk. ;qA&AePortal)  z030028408Xq(hardcover)  z9780300278347q(hardcover)  aILObengerdaepncILOdOCLCOdYUSdOCLCO 4aNK8802.C47bA7825 2025eb2 aArt Institute of Chicago,ehost institution,eorganizer,epublisher.10aOn loss and absence :btextiles of mourning and survival /cedited by Isaac Facio, Nneka Kai, L Vinebaum, Anne Wilson ; contributions by Jerry Bleem, Valerie Cassel Oliver, Gustavo Da Silva, Isaac Facio, Wafa Ghnaim, Jen Chen-su Huang, Nneka Kai, Cristian Koepfli, Alipio Melo, Sarah Molina, María José Murillo, Lucinda Pelton, Sharbreon Plummer, Jenni Sorkin, Barbara Teller Ornelas, Lynda Teller Pete, Cybele Tom, L Vinebaum, Melinda Watt, Danitza Willka, Anne Wilson, Folayemi Wilson.30aTextiles of mourning and survival  aFirst edition. 1aChicago :bArt Institute of Chicago,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (207 pages) :b155 illustrations (chiefly color), portraits  astill imagebsti2rdacontent0http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/contentTypes/sti  atextbtxt2rdacontent0http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/contentTypes/txt  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  a"Published in conjunction with an exhibition of the same title organized by the Art Institute of Chicago, September 6, 2025-March 15, 2026"--Colophon.  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.2 aIntroduction : Textiles of Mourning and Survival / Isaac Facio, Nneka Kai, L Vinebaum, Anne Wilson -- The Geometry of Loss / Valerie Cassel Oliver -- Grief and Disconsolate Forgetting : Objects of Mourning in the Context of Empire and Slavery / Jenni Sorkin -- Silent Witness : Ancient Textiles as Biocultural Archives of Disease and Human History / Gustavo Da Silva, Isaac Facio, Cristian Koepfli, Lucinda Pelon -- Of Water and Sky Along a Fibered Path / Folayemi Wilson -- For Eighteen Looped Clouds / Jen Chen-su Huang -- Fragmentary Understanding : Textiles in the Encyclopedic Museum / Melinda Watt -- Wounds, Scars, and a Bandage / Jerry Bleem -- Representing and Re-Presenting Textiles / Sarah Molina, Cybele Tom -- The Timelessness of Tatreez : Stitched Stories of Palestinian Makers Once Known / Wafa Ghnaim -- Material Inheritances, Lasting 'Til Sunday / Nneka Kai -- The Heartbeat of Andean Weaving / Alipio Melo, María José Murillo, Danitza Willka -- Rembrance as Resistance : The Quilts of Dorothy Burge / Sharbreon Plummer -- The Enduring Beauty of Diné Textiles / Lynda Teller Pete, Barbara Teller Ornelas.  a"From ancient Egyptian shrouds to medieval relics, textiles have played both functional and symbolic roles in rituals of death across time and place. Featuring funeral hangings, mourning samplers, garments, and many other textiles and fragments, along with works by contemporary textile artists such as Nick Cave (b. 1959) and Angela Hennessey (b. 1971), this book highlights how these objects help people negotiate experiences of loss, grief, healing, and survival. With over seventy textiles dating from antiquity to today, 'On Loss and Absence' brings together examples from cultures and traditions around the world"--Publisher's description.  aDescription based on print version record and online resource (A&AePortal, viewed on March 12, 2026) 0aDecoration and ornamentxPsychological aspects. 0aDecoration and ornamentxPsychological aspectsvExhibitions. 0aMourning customs. 0aMourning customsvExhibitions. 0aNeedleworkzIllinoiszChicago. 0aNeedleworkzIllinoiszChicagovExhibitions. 0aTextile fabricszIllinoiszChicago. 0aTextile fabricszIllinoiszChicagovExhibitions. 7aExhibition catalogs.2lcgft1 aFacio, Isaac,eeditor,econtributor.4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1http://id.loc.gov/rwo/agents/no20221514001 aKai, Nneka,eeditor,econtributor.4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1http://id.loc.gov/rwo/agents/no20251280811 aVinebaum, Lisa,cPhD,eeditor,econtributor.4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PCjtmKk8CTD86C3hJfk4hxP1https://isni.org/isni/00000003830425741 aWilson, Anne,d1949-eeditor,econtributor.4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PBJrWDXChTwyt3hTrFqWCcP1https://isni.org/isni/000000007869615X2 aYale University Press,epublisher.  1http://id.loc.gov/resources/instances/24258500  4http://id.loc.gov/ontologies/bibframe/instanceOf1http://id.loc.gov/resources/works/2425850008iPrint version:aArt Institute of Chicago.tOn loss and absencez9780300284089w(OCoLC)1499258735403A&AePortal (Yale University Press)uhttps://aaeportal.com/?id=-10123704075cam a2200445 i 1587612065OCoLC20260504163552.0m     o  d        cr mn|||||||||260501t20252025ctuab   ob    001 0 eng d  a0300293070q(electronic bk.;qA&AePortal)  a9780300293074q(electronic bk.;qA&AePortal)  z0300256493q(hardcover)  z9780300256499q(hardcover)  aYUSbengerdaepncYUSdYUSdOCLCO  an-us-ny0http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/geographicAreas/n-us-ny 4aNA9350.N5bR43 2025eb1 aReason, Akela,eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PCjHPkQTWQjRGykXKmvXdjP1http://id.loc.gov/rwo/agents/n200904151210aPolitics and memory :bCivil War monuments in Gilded Age New York /cAkela Reason.30aCivil War monuments in Gilded Age New York 1aNew Haven ;aLondon :bYale University Press,c[2025] 4c©2025  a1 online resource (ix, 291 pages) :b119 illustrations (color and black & white), map  astill imagebsti2rdacontent0http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/contentTypes/sti  atextbtxt2rdacontent0http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/contentTypes/txt  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.20g1.tObelisk : the Worth Monument and the making of New York's commemorative landscape to the Civil War --g2.tThe standing soldier in the cemetery : New York's earliest soldiers' monuments --g3.tThe standing soldier in the public sphere : the influence of private patronage --g4.tThe shaft monument : democratic designs in Brooklyn --g5.tThe arch : the Brooklyn Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument --g6.tTholos : the New York Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument --tThe afterlives of New York's soldier's monuments.  a"In the decades following the Civil War, New York City built more monuments to the Union cause than any other city in the nation outside of Washington, DC. Ranging from simple standing soldiers to grand triumphal arches and temples, these monuments shaped commemorative aesthetics and iconography at the local and national levels. Unlike Confederate monuments, which were mostly initiated by private organizations, New York's soldiers' monuments were largely supported through city and state funding. These civic projects attracted the interest of competing groups, including artists, politicians, veterans, and the public, that all sought to influence the growing commemorative landscape. Works such as the Brooklyn Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument outside Prospect Park and the New York Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument in Riverside Park were created in a fractious political landscape and defined as much by municipal maneuvering as by artistic principle. Illuminating the historical context of Civil War soldiers' monuments in New York City, Akela Reason explores the complex and fascinating intersection of art, politics, and memory within these works, while also highlighting the ever-changing ways different constituencies have engaged with them in symbolic and physical terms"--Publisher's description.  aDescription based on print version record and online resource (A&AePortal, viewed on May 1, 2026). 0aArt and societyzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy19th century. 0aPublic sculpture, AmericanzNew York (State)zNew Yorky19th century. 0aSoldiers' monumentszNew York (State)zNew Yorky19th century. 0aWar memorialszNew York (State)zNew Yorky19th century. 0aUnited StatesxHistoryyCivil War, 1861-1865xMonuments.2 aYale University Press,epublisher.08iPrint version:aReason, Akela.tPolitics and memoryz9780300256499w(DLC)  2024946015w(OCoLC)1464948687403A&AePortal (Yale University Press)uhttps://aaeportal.com/?id=-10119003238cam a2200433 i 1587613943OCoLC20260504163611.0m     o  d        cr mn|||||||||260501s2012    ctuac   ob    001 0 eng d  a0300303467q(electronic bk.;qA&AePortal)  a9780300303469q(electronic bk.;qA&AePortal)  z030017733Xq(paperback)  z9780300177336q(paperback)  aYUSbengerdaepncYUSdYUSdOCLCO 4aND467.5.P7bB28 2012eb1 aBarringer, T. J.,eauthor.1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PCjyWxj77RT9hJqhJ9pJQjd10aReading the Pre-Raphaelites /cTim Barringer.  aRev. ed. 1aNew Haven, CT :bYale University Press,c2012.  a1 online resource (192 pages) :b118 illustrations (chiefly color), portraits  astill imagebsti2rdacontent  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  a"First published in Great Britain in 1998 by George Weidenfeld and Nicolson Ltd."  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 186-188) and index.2 aNote on the revised edition -- 1. Rebellion and revivalism -- 2. Truth to nature -- 3. Modern life -- 4. Art, religion and empire -- 5. Pre-Raphaelites and aesthetes.  a"Noted for its vivid colors, elaborate use of symbols, and dedication to close observation of the natural world, the work of Pre-Raphaelite artists combines a deep engagement with the past and a modern realism that exemplifies the concerns of the age of steam travel. In Reading the Pre-Raphaelites, author Tim Barringer draws on an imaginative selection of paintings, drawings, and photographs to suggest that the dynamic energy of Pre-Raphaelitism arose out of the paradoxes at its heart. Past and present, historicism and modernity, symbolism and realism, as well as the tensions between city and country, men and women, worker and capitalist, colonizer and colonized all make appearances within Pre-Raphaelite art. By focusing on these issues, Barringer draws together the strands of revisionist thought on the Pre-Raphaelites and provides a range of stimulating new interpretations of their work. The revised edition of this authoritative survey traces the history of the Pre-Raphaelite movement, and includes new sections on photography as well as a revised introduction and bibliography"--Publisher's description.  aDescription based on print version record and online resource (A&AePortal, viewed on May 1, 2026). 0aArt, Englishy19th century. 0aPre-Raphaelites. 0aPre-Raphaelitism. 7aPre-Raphaelite.2aat2 aYale University Press,epublisher.08iRevision of:aBarringer, T. J.tPre-Raphaelites.dLondon : Weidenfeld and Nicolson, ©1998z0297824082w(OCoLC)4097037808iPrint version:aBarringer, T. J.tReading the Pre-Raphaelites.bRev. ed.dNew Haven, CT : Yale University Press, 2012z9780300177336w(DLC)  2011037516w(OCoLC)752910623403A&AePortal (Yale University Press)uhttps://aaeportal.com/?id=-10122303978cam a2200481 i 1588480955OCoLC20260504163641.0m     o  d        cr mn|||||||||260504t19811978ctua    o     000 0 eng d  a0300303483q(electronic bk.;qA&AePortal)  a9780300303483q(electronic bk.;qA&AePortal)  z0300021933q(hardcover)  z0300027761q(paperback)  z9780300021936q(hardcover)  z9780300027761q(paperback)  aYUSbengerdaepncYUSdYUS  ae-fr---ae-uk-enae-ne--- 4aNK2043b.T45 1981eb1 aThornton, Peter,d1925-2007,eauthor.1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PBJv8KrXRxH4Vff9tYj8Bfq10aSeventeenth-century interior decoration in England, France, and Holland /cPeter Thornton.3 a17th-century interior decoration in England, France, and Holland  a2nd print. (with corrections). 1aNew Haven ;aLondon :bPublished for the Paul Mellon Centre for Studies in British Art by Yale University Press,c1981. 4c©1978  a1 online resource (xii, 427 pages) :b339 illustrations (some color)  astill imagebsti2rdacontent  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier1 aStudies in British art2 aFrance and Aristocratic Fashion -- The Spread of the French Ideal -- The Architectural Framework -- The Upholsterer's Task -- The Upholsterer's Materials -- The Upholsterer's Furnishings -- Beds, Cloths of Estate and Couches -- Upholstered Seat-furniture -- Tables and Cup-boards -- Other Furniture and Decorative Features -- Lighting -- Specific Rooms and Their Decoration.  a"This is the first book to survey and analyze the development of European interior decoration in France, England, and Holland following the stimulus of the Italian Renaissance while relating it to the changes in the political structure and social habits of the landed classes at the end of the sixteenth century. Working from surviving examples of the furniture and decoration of the period, and making full use of engraved and painted records, inventories, and other documentary evidence, Peter Thornton investigates and explains the role and intentions of the architect, the upholsterer, and the furniture-maker in the creation of the fashionable interior. He emphasizes that during the seventeenth century it was often through the personal supervision of the interior decoration of a great house by its owner that a hitherto unknown degree of comfort and unity of design came to prevail. The arrangement and decoration of the rooms, their furnishings and hangings, paneling and carpeting, lighting and sanitation are all discussed in detail with due attention being given to the designers and craftsmen concerned and the materials and techniques used"--Publisher's description.  aDescription based on print version record and online resource (A&AePortal, viewed on May 1, 2026). 0aInterior decorationzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aInterior decorationzFrancexHistoryy17th century. 0aInterior decorationzNetherlandsxHistoryy17th century.2 aPaul Mellon Centre for Studies in British Art.1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39QH7JmmPqBgbrH3VJqgdDbM62 aYale University Press,epublisher.08iPrint version:aThornton, Peter, 1925-2007.tSeventeenth-century interior decoration in England, France, and Holland.b2nd print. (with corrections).dNew Haven : Published for the Paul Mellon Centre for Studies in British Art by Yale University Press, 1981, ©1978z0300021933w(DLC)   77091067w(OCoLC)609594599 0aStudies in British art (Unnumbered)403A&AePortal (Yale University Press)uhttps://aaeportal.com/?id=-10130203343cam a2200469 i 1588482006OCoLC20260504163513.0m     o  d        cr mn|||||||||260504t20242024ctuabe  ob    001 0 eng d  a0300306024q(electronic bk.;qA&AePortal)  a9780300306026q(electronic bk.;qA&AePortal)  z0300270038q(hardcover)  z9780300270037q(hardcover)  aYUSbengerdaepncYUSdYUS  ae------aaw-----aff----- 4aN5763b.H67 2024eb1 aHopkins, John North,eauthor.1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PCjF3T7qF6kYqgxBVrHtVG310aUnbound from Rome :bart and craft in a fluid landscape, ca. 650-250 BCE /cJohn North Hopkins.30aArt and craft in a fluid landscape, circa 650-250 BCE 1aNew Haven ;aLondon :bYale University Press,c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (vii, 240 pages) :b136 illustrations (chiefly color), maps (chiefly color), black and white plans  astill imagebsti2rdacontent  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 210-232) and index.2 aMaking space for makers : recovering presence, capability, action, and contribution -- Making space for many makers and materials : compounding mobile copresences -- Beyond control : time, accumulation, and multiplication -- Meaning unmoored : creative assemblage and entropic potentials in the Ficoroni Cista -- The quiet, effective disorder of sacromaterial practice -- Unending views.  a"Moving beyond the misleading catchall label 'Roman,' John North Hopkins aims to untangle the many peoples whose diverse cultures and traditions contributed to Rome's visual culture over a four-hundred-year time span across the first millennium BCE. Hopkins carefully reconsiders some of the period's most iconic works by way of the many practices and peoples bound up with them. Some of these include the extraordinary and complex effort to build the Temple of Jupiter; the creative actions and diverse encounters tied to luxury objects like the Ficoroni Cista; and the important meanings held by sacred temple sculpture and votive offerings through their making and subsequent practices of devotion. A key purpose of this book is to question an idea of Rome that has focused on elite production and the textual record; Hopkins instead calls attention to the lesser-known-- often silenced-- actors who were integral players"--Publisher's description.  aDescription based on print version record and online resource (A&AePortal, viewed on May 4, 2026). 0aArchitecture and societyzRome. 0aArchitecture, Roman. 0aArt and societyzRome. 0aArt, Roman. 0aDecoration and ornament, Roman. 0aDecoration and ornamentxSocial aspectszRome. 0aRomexAntiquities.2 aYale University Press,epublisher.08iPrint version:aHopkins, John North,tUnbound from Romez9780300270037w(DLC)  2023941072w(OCoLC)1375542816403A&AePortal (Yale University Press)uhttps://aaeportal.com/?id=-10128902907cam a2200409 i 1588483215OCoLC20260504163657.0m     o  d        cr mn|||||||||260504s2004    ctuib   ob    001 0 eng d  a0300303211q(electronic bk.;qA&AePortal)  a9780300303216q(electronic bk.;qA&AePortal)  z0300107234q(paperback)  z9780300107234q(paperback)  aYUSbengerdaepncYUSdYUS  ae-ne--- 4aND1452.N43bW48 2004eb1 aWestermann, Mariët,eauthor.1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PCjBFkbb9gwxhq9ycDcv3jP12aA worldly art :bthe Dutch Republic, 1585-1718 /cMariët Westermann.  aReprinted ed. 1aNew Haven, CT :bYale University Press,c[2004?]  a1 online resource (192 pages) :bcolor illustrations, black & white maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.2 a1. Making and marketing pictures in the Dutch Republic -- 2. Texts and images -- 3. Virtual realities -- 4. Dutch ideologies and nascent national identity -- 5. Portraiture and the identity of self and community -- 6. Artistic authority.1 a"Newly independent in 1585, the increasingly prosperous and politically powerful Dutch Republic experienced a tremendous rise in the production of artwork that was unparalleled in quantity, variety, and beauty. Now back in print, this classic book (originally published in 1996) examines the country's rich artistic culture in the seventeenth century, providing a full account of Dutch artists and patrons; artistic themes and techniques; and the political and social world in which artists worked. Distinguished art historian Mariet Westermann examines the 'worldly art' of this time in the context of the unique society that produced it, analyzing artists' choices and demonstrating how their pictures tell particular stories about the Dutch Republic, its people, and its past. Updated color illustrations complement this engaging discussion of an extraordinary moment in the history of art"--Publisher's description.  aDescription based on print version record and online resource (A&AePortal, viewed on May 4, 2026). 0aArt and societyzNetherlandsxHistoryy17th century. 0aGenre painting, Dutchy17th century. 0aPainting, Dutchy17th century. 0aRealism in art.2 aYale University Press,epublisher.08iPrint version:aWestermann, Mariët,tWorldly art.bReprinted ed.dNew Haven, CT : Yale University Press, 2004z9780300107234w(DLC)  2004113043w(OCoLC)58450987403A&AePortal (Yale University Press)uhttps://aaeportal.com/?id=-101204